@node Overview " Overview "

 OVERVIEW:

 What does it do?

 An AmiTCP Frontend for both SLIP and PPP connections to the InterNET!

 Basically,this program simplifies the connection, and disconnection from your
 Internet Provider.
 The program  also keeps a record  of any dial-in  attempts made by you  in  a
 logfile located in a user-defined Log-File.

 Why?

 Easy.  I only have  4 meg of RAM,  run workbench on a PAL  Hires screen,  and
 don't have the desktop space / ram to waste on windows/docks which I use very
 rarely.
 Face it, even if you DO have a huge amount of ram, do you WANT a stupid  util
 using up resources, which you use only twice in about 3 hours? Naaaahh..
 God, I pity those still using 2 meg ram, connecting to the net! Nightmare!
 Also,I found that the existing dialers/frontends which currently exist either
 didn't actually work, crashed horrendously, or just damned ugly to start with
 ...I also thought that most of their startnet and dialing sequences to be full
 of useless irrelevant junk...the one that comes with AmiTCP is stupidly HUGE!!
 Why ?? Jeez...
@endnode

@node Requirements

What is needed exactly?

- AmiTCP/IP protocol stack
  Versions 3.0b or higher. You can find a demo of AmiTCP v 4 on the Aminet,
        comm/tcp/AmiTCP_demo_40.lha
  I have heard that the layout of AmiTCP 4.3 is remarkeably different from
  previous versions, and this MAY not work with it. This of course applies
  to all the other frontends, but..we'll see.

- PPP device driver
  The PPP.device is a commercial application, meaning you have to pay to
  have full useability of this device. There is a demo version on the Aminet
  in comm/net/PPP_144.lha which is perfectly fine for most uses, as there
  are no time/transfer size limits.

- ARexx Version 1.15 or above.
  Comes as standard with Workbench 2.04 and above.
  Make sure you have activated the AREXX host, by entering somewhere into
  your startup the line
             Run >NIL: <NIL: SYS:System/Rexxmast

- System Library Files  (All found on Aminet)
    Libs:reqtools.library          	Version 38.1296 or above.
    Libs:rexxreqtools.library           Version 37.71 or above.
    Libs:rexxarplib.library Version 	Version 1.0 or above.

- External Utilities (Not Provided with TCPFront)
    C:IconX               Eeerm, comes with Workbench.  :)
    AmiTCP:bin/OLT	  V1.2 © 1995 Paul Huxham
	(Paul, if you don't want me to use this prog, please contact me,
         as my email to your provided address was bounced)
    C:DSound		  IFF Sound HD spooler. by Dave Schreiber
			  (I don't have a contact email addr for you
			   so, again, scream at me.  )   ;))

-   A Brain (Usually comes as standard with ManOS v0.01 and upwards)
    In case you don't have one, or have accidentally misplaced it,
    inform me ASAP so I can make loadsa money out of you, and apply
    to your local Mortuary or Organ Donor Repository for a replacement.
@endnode

@node Installation " Installation "
 INSTALLATION:

 Note : You _MUST_ have AmiTCP Installed already for this to work.
        I will not guide your through Installing AmiTCP, as this takes
        over the startnet and link sections of AmiTCP. All you have to do
        is make sure AmiTCP is correctly installed (ie, have all the files
	in the right places).

        Also, YOU must install PPP.device yourself, TCPFront does not,
        as it is a commercial package.
        What dialer you use (whether internal or external to ppp.device)
        is entirely up to you.

        IF PPP.device fails to dial in, ie it locks up without contacting
        the modem, either change yor dialer (I recommend dialerdevice17.lha
        on the Aminet) or contact the author of PPP.device for help,
        NOT me. Only contact me with problems/suggestions for TCPFront.

 I have based the SLIP support in TCPFront on an environment variable
 called 'Slip0State'. Now, I am unsure if ALL slip drivers create/use
 this, so check if it is compatible or not by typing into the shell :

       getenv slip0state

 This should return "Online" when you are online, and "Offline" when,
 obviously, you are Offline. If not, or this variable does not exist,
 please email me and I'll see what I can do. Obviously only check
 when AmiTCP is running.  :)

 Installation :
     You should use the provided Install.BAT script.

 You are advised to keep a backup of the config somewhere....sod it.
 @{"Here" link ConfigBackup} is a backup in case you need it.

                And that 'should' be it!
@endnode

@node Usage

 Usage :

   From shell, type
           rx AmiTCP:bin/TCPFront.rexx >NIL:

   Easy. Just follow the prompts.

   This is ideal for users of Toolmanager/AmiDOCK, or other dock like
   programs. Also excellent when used in conjuntion with a function key,
   like F1.

   Anyone wanna make up a MagicWB/NewIcons/Iconographics Icon for this,
   you're more than welcome...just uuencode and email me it!  :)
@endnode

@node UsageNotes

 Usage Hints :

 I personally have  assigned the F1 key to call this program,  which you
 can do using a utility like fkey which comes with Workbench, or some similar
 program found on the Aminet.

 Also excellent for Toolmanager/AmiDOCK users...just one button instead of
 twenty!  ;)

 If you experience any SERIOUS problems,  EMail me at once and revert back to
 your original TCP dialing sequence (well, you'd have to wouldn't you? hehe)

 If you experience any MINOR problems, again, EMail me at once and I will try
 to remedy  the situation  and email  you the repaired  program as soon as  is
 sanely possible. But please don't bug me on it.  :)

 If you have any problems using the internal dialer provided with  PPP.device
 ( ie it doesn't work ) you should change your serial device : there are
 several available on the aminet, such as artser.device, 8n1.device...

 If the internal dialer STILL  doesn't work ( I certainly couldn't  get it to
 work ) then I advise you to download another dialer from the aminet.
 I personally recommend dialer.device (dialerdevice17.lha) off aminet.

 If you use this  device,  all you then need to do is  type the  following in
 your shell :

 Echo "dialer.device 0 19200 0.0.0.0 MTU=1500 7WIRE" >ENV:Sana2/ppp0.config
 Copy ENV:Sana2/PPP0.config ENVARC:Sana2/

 The wiser amongst you will have noticed this is a VERY basic installation of
 ppp.device,  but it's what I use,  and it does me fine. Don't fix what ain't
 broken.

 It really IS pants to set up ppp with amitcp...believe me!  You just need to
 sit down and figure out what it's trying to do....

 And that's it! Mail me if you still have problems.
@endnode

